entry.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
entry.content: 10 or so plants on the edge of a very lush depression. This is the second known population of this plant in Victoria. Peter Barnes led us to this population which he has known about for many years. ID confirmed by Neville Walsh.

entry.title: Hypoxis glabella var. glabella
entry.content: New species record for Neds Corner. ID confirmed by Neville Walsh. Photos show some features required for determination at species level (eg. two non-sheathing bracteoles towards the base of the flower stem - see 3rd photo). This taxon has recently changed name from Hypoxis glabella.

entry.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
entry.content: Location is where the species was discovered in Victoria in 2011.

entry.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
entry.content: Location is where this species was discovered for Victoria in 2011, until now the only population known in Victoria. The plant in the first two pics was in dry soil at the outer edge of a gilgai and exposed to full sun. This made this plant a little depauperate. This plant also had the best flower at this location. Plants were found both sides of the track in the numerous small depressions/gilgais, always at the outer edge of the depression.

entry.title: Elachanthus pusillus
entry.content: Red-tipped and fringed bracts are a key feature of this species. Single individual of this tiny herb found among large numbers of Elachanthus glaber covering an area of just about 20m x 10m. Elachanthus pusillus is considerably smaller than E. glaber and has red-tipped and fringed apex to bracts plus bristly-hairy leaves. E. glaber has none of these features.
